<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / International Capital Markets: Mexican and Hungarian issues
break new ground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Financial Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEXICO and Hungary broke new ground in the US bond market last week,
launching the first Yankee bond issues by sub-investment grade sovereign
borrowers.
Mexico brought a Dollars 250m offering of 10-year bonds priced to yield 215
basis points above the 10-year treasury yield. Goldman Sachs, which arranged
the transaction, said the deal was being placed with mainstream Yankee bond
investors.
Meanwhile, Hungary became the first eastern European country to raise funds
in the US bond market, with a Dollars 200m 10-year deal via Salomon Brothers
priced to yield 275 basis points over the 10-year treasury yield - wider
than the original indication of 250 basis points.
Hungary has now completed around Dollars 900m of its Dollars 1bn funding
programme for this year, and expects to raise the same amount in the capital
markets next year.
Mexico is rated BB-plus by S&amp;P and Ba2 by Moody's while Hungary has BB-plus
from S&amp;P and Ba1 from Moody's.
</TEXT>
