<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / European Bonds: French voters do little to close divisions
in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The lukewarm support delivered by French voters yesterday for the EC's
proposed economic and monetary union is likely to do little to reverse the
forces that had already opened up sharp divisions within the European
exchange rate mechanism.
The foreign exchange market decided last week to exercise its own vote
before the French got round to theirs, and its verdict seems unlikely to be
reversed now.
'An event that doesn't have broad European significance,' was the view of Mr
Richard Grey, a bond market analyst with UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, ahead of the
vote.
However, the result is still likely to have some important ramifications:
for instance, in deciding the fate of the French franc, and the future
direction of the French bond market.
If the franc survives the current ERM crisis without a forced devaluation -
an outcome that appeared more likely as the currency strengthened last night
 -then 'it will virtually have become a Deutsche mark,' said Ms Alison
Cottrell, an economist at Midland Montagu.
The foreign exchange markets, which were developing a taste for bashing the
franc at the end of last week, are likely to back off somewhat after the
referendum result - though the narrowness of the victory means the currency
is not out of the woods yet.
The second result of a Yes vote could be an attempt by European politicians
to patch up at least some of their differences of the last few days, and
perhaps even to try to keep the Maastricht timetable for Emu on the road.
That could merely serve to delay the inevitable. Ratification of the
Maastricht Treaty in other member states will not be easy, given the
narrowness of the French support, the messages from the currency markets in
recent days and the ill-will generated between some European leaders during
the course of last week.
As a result, Europe's bond markets at the end of last week were already
reflecting a lack of belief in the future of EMU, preferring instead to take
a fresh look at the economic fundamentals of individual member states.
A clear indicator of this was the speed with which the gilt market's
inverted yield curve fell flat on its back.
The market's mood did a smart about-turn during the course of the week, at
least at the short end of the yield curve. As sterling slid, the market
began to look for a two point cut in base rates, from the current 10 per
cent.
Meanwhile, longer-dated gilt yields had begun to creep up, to around 200
basis points above German levels, as the spectre of renewed inflation
threatened to return. However, most analysts discounted the likelihood of a
renewed burst of inflation given the depth of the UK's current recession -
even allowing for the effects of the falling pound  - and the relative
firmness in the gilt market reflected this view.
The beliefs which have shaped both ends of the yield curve in recent days
could turn out to be over-optimistic. It seems unlikely, for instance, that
the UK government is about to abandon its anti-inflation strategy quite so
quickly.
With a general election won less than six months ago, Mr John Major's
government is under no immediate pressure to engineer an economic boom to
appease voters. Also, a sharp drop in rates could cause sterling to plunge,
further undermining attempts to restrain inflation.
Even if the UK does not opt to tie its currency into the ERM in the near
term, it can hardly ignore the power of German interest rates, which will
continue to dictate monetary conditions in Europe.
'If we are still in the same anti-inflationary world, you have to look at
Germany,' said Mr John Shepperd, economist at SG Warburg.
At the longer end of the market, meanwhile, yields could be set to rise
sharply from their current levels. Even leaving aside the danger of renewed
inflation, there remains the question of how the UK will finance its fiscal
deficit.
Analysts doubt that any economic upturn resulting from devaluation will show
through in an increased tax yield or lower social securities payments until
the second half of next year.
In the meantime, international investors will demand an extra risk premium
for holding sterling.
It will be difficult to persuade UK investors to take up the slack. The
renewed appetite among UK insurers and pension funds for gilts in recent
months was based on the assumption that the UK was facing a low-growth,
low-inflation decade, making fixed-income investments more attractive than
equities.
If those assumptions are reversed, gilt yields will have to rise to persuade
investors to keep funding the UK's deficit.
The precipitate decision to float sterling last week has made an immediate
impact on investors. 'I've got to say that it does look as though it has
shifted the pattern in favour of equities,' said Mr Mike Sandland, chief
investment manager of Norwich Union, the UK insurer. Norwich Union had done
more than any other investor over the previous months to lead the move away
from equities and into gilts.
The clear winner from the dislocation of the ERM so far has been the bund
market - with other 'core' government bonds markets, like that of the Dutch,
closely in tow. However, over time, the events of the last few days could
prove to have contradictory effects on the German market.
On the positive side, bunds will benefit from disarray in other currencies -
though to a large extent, investors from outside Europe had already looked
to the D-Mark block when investing in the EC.
The result will be to buoy the currency further, helping to slow its decline
against the US dollar. A high D-Mark will make German exports less
competitive, adding to the slowing in the German economy and so making bunds
more attractive.
On the negative side, any further slowdown in Germany could exacerbate the
fiscal deficit, adding to the weight of supply in the bond market (and with
much of this year's deficit still to be financed).
Also, the sharp spike in money supply from all the ill-starred intervention
on the foreign exchanges in recent days could hold back the speed of
interest rate reductions. If the politicians decide to call it a day on
Maastricht, the pressure on Germany to cut its interest rates will also
diminish.
Against this background, the French bond market could yet turn out to be one
of the major gainers from the events of last week and yesterday's narrow
vote.
The country's strong economic fundamentals have long been recognised by
international bond investors, though their appetite for OATs has been slight
during the uncertain summer months.
With uncertainty finally out of the way - at least for the French market -
the market's fundamental attractions could return to the fore.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
