<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / International Company News: DAF confirms it is in talks with
Japanese truck maker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DAF, the loss-making Dutch commercial vehicle maker which is already holding
negotiations on a strategic alliance with Mercedes-Benz of Germany, said
last night it was also holding co-operation talks with a Japanese truck
producer.
It is believed to be discussing collaboration, most probably for the
development and supply of components, with Hino Motors, one of the leading
Japanese heavy truck makers and part of the Toyota group of companies.
DAF confirmed last night that Mr Cor Baan, chairman of the DAF management
board, had held talks recently in Tokyo with a Japanese truck producer, but
it refused to disclose the identity of its partner in the talks.
Toyota, the biggest Japanese car maker, holds a direct stake of 11 per cent
in Hino with which it has been linked since 1966.
DAF, in which British Aerospace holds a 16 per cent stake, said that it had
decided 'not to reveal how substantive these talks are' with the Japanese
producer.
Confirmation of the discussions in Japan follows the disclosure last month
that DAF had begun talks on forming a 'strategic alliance' with
Mercedes-Benz, the world's leading truck maker.
It is understood that the collaboration discussions now under way with Hino
are not as far-reaching in scope as the negotiations with Mercedes-Benz.
While DAF refused publicly to name Mercedes-Benz, the automotive subsidiary
of Daimler-Benz, Germany's biggest industrial corporation, as its potential
partner, Dutch trade union officials confirmed the talks between the two
companies.
DAF, which is suffering its third year of heavy losses, said last month that
discussions were 'taking place on a strategic alliance', which could lead to
a 'structural strengthening' of the group.
An equity stake was under consideration and the negotiations included talks
on exchanging products, co-operation in product development and sharing of
production.
Mercedes-Benz admitted that discussions were under way, but it insisted that
the talks only concerned the creation of a 'customer/supplier relationship'
between the two.
Hino's presence in Europe has been limited to small-volume assembly of its
trucks in Ireland.
</TEXT>
