FT  21 SEP 92 / International Company News: Hewlett to take one-off charge
of Dollars 544m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HEWLETT-Packard (HP) is taking a Dollars 544m one-time charge before tax to
adopt a revised method of accounting for the cost of medical insurance for
retired employees.
The accounting change will result in a Dollars 332m after tax reduction in
fiscal 1992 earnings.
HP is one of several US corporations that have adopted the new rule, set
down by the Financial Accounting Standards Board, which requires companies
to include in their accounts the long-term costs of medical benefits
obligations.
HP's first-quarter earnings, originally reported as Dollars 306m, or Dollars
1.21 per share, have been restated as losses of Dollars 30m to reflect the
charge.
Additional 1992 expenses, as a result of the accounting change, will be
approximately Dollars 23m pre-tax.
