</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ALGIERS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALGERIA'S new government promised austerity and more taxes but offered
incentives to foreign investors in an ambitious plan to achieve a market
economy and end violence, Reuter reports from Algiers. It warned 'rigorous
austerity, drastically reducing the need to import' was coming.
The rich will be taxed more on income, with a separate tax on assets; tax
breaks will go to innovative companies replacing imported goods, and
competing imports will be banned.
A 'vast field of activities' will open for local and foreign investors with
incentives, including favourable exchange rates for investment.
