<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Maastricht - The Economic Fallout: European officials
display their relief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN finance ministers and monetary officials meeting at the
International Monetary Fund in Washington yesterday put the best face on
things as they reacted to the first news of France's vote on the Maastricht
treaty, write George Graham and Peter Norman.
Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister, acknowledged that the Yes vote
had only narrowly prevailed but said, as he disappeared into a meeting with
his fellow EC finance ministers, that the result would still be enough to
calm the markets.
'A small majority is better than a minority. It is a good result. It is a
positive signal for the integration of Europe. It is a positive for the
markets.'
His optimism was endorsed by some European central bankers.
Mr Helmut Schlesinger, president of the Bundesbank, said the result 'will
certainly calm down the markets' while Mr Lamberto Dini, director general of
the Italian central bank, agreed it was positive.
French officials cheerfully maintained that even a narrow Yes would restore
calm to the markets.
One suggested the EC ministers' most important business in their meeting
would be the ceremonial opening of champagne bottles.
Some officials privately acknowledged, however, that the mood in private
meetings was far less cheerful. 'Any closer and we would all have been
diving for cover,' said one European diplomat.
'We're not out of the woods yet,' a senior EC official added.
</TEXT>
