<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Insolvency Service fees and funding under review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is undertaking a detailed review of the way in which the
official Insolvency Service is funded after strong criticism of the existing
system.
Among the issues under discussion is the reform of the insolvency services
account, which funds the service from the proceeds of assets realised from
insolvent companies and individuals.
The Insolvency Service deals with corporate and individual financial failure
and tackles wrongdoing within insolvencies. It is an executive agency of the
Department of Trade and Industry under the government's Next Steps
initiative.
Whitehall officials have confirmed that a review is under way. It will cover
some of the most important aspects of how the service is funded and the
structure of its fees.
Under the present timetable, ministers will have a report by early December.
Private insolvency practitioners have long complained that the insolvency
services account - which is administered by officials - is inefficient and
penalises creditors.
The existing system of finance means that the creditors of insolvent
companies and individuals are the ones who are paying for the service.
The proceeds of any asset sales from compulsory liquidations and
bankruptcies must be placed in the account, as well as those from other
liquidation procedures under certain conditions.
The account offers a low, fixed rate of interest which is taxed before any
proceeds can be removed. Some portion of the money can be placed into the
insolvency service investment account, which allows proceeds to be invested
in gilts and Treasury bills.
The Insolvency Service is at present running at a substantial surplus,
generating income from fees and the insolvency services account of Pounds
62m in the last financial year, against costs of Pounds 57m. The extra was
paid to the DTI.
The review is unlikely to propose any options that reduce the chance of the
service to be self-funding. But it will consider whether it is possible to
retain income generated rather than remitting it to the Treasury each year.
Among alternative proposals for raising money being considered is an
additional charge that would be paid by all limited liability companies as
part of their annual registration fee, or a fixed-rate fee levied on the
proceeds of asset realisations.
Historically, one of the reasons for the insolvency services account was to
prevent unscrupulous practitioners misappropriating funds left in their own
hands.
The 1986 insolvency act introduced a licensing system in which practitioners
are also required to put up a bond that could be cashed if there was any
suspicion of creditors' money being used improperly.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
