<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Shelter sees rise in debt victims
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
RECORD NUMBERS of homeowners are turning to the housing charity Shelter
because of mortgage debt.
The number of homeowners threatened with repossession seeking the charity's
advice increased by half last year.
Homeowners now accounted for one in seven of those wanting its help, Shelter
said in its annual report.
Ms Sheila McKechnie, a Shelter director, said: 'The changing face of our
caseload reflects the continuing debt crisis that is still swamping new
victims every day.
'Shelter has directly helped thousands of people stay in their homes in the
short term . . . but there has never been more urgency in our national
campaign for more affordable housing for rent.'
The charity reported an increase of 24 per cent in income to more than
Pounds 7m.
