<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Auditors report fierce competition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY SMALL firms of chartered accountants are experiencing severe price
competition for audit work, according to the findings of a new survey.
'Lowballing' or predatory pricing by rival firms for audit bids has caused
concern for nearly two thirds of a sample of 46 members of the CharterGroup
partnership, an association of accountancy firms.
Many firms have reported anecdotally over the past few months that they have
been coming under pressure to reduce audit fees. That has been driven by
many companies putting audits out to tender while accountancy firms have
been eager to gain business because of the effects of the recession.
The ethics committee of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England
and Wales was sufficiently concerned about lowballing to circulate a
discussion paper on the subject.
Sixty-three per cent of the CharterGroup survey said the present extent of
lowballing was sufficient to warrant concern, and 76 per cent believed it
would lead to a lowering of audit standards.
Four fifths believe there should be extended ethical guidance on the subject
from the institute.
Eighty-eight per cent of firms believe that accountants would recover low
income from audits by providing other services to their clients.
Sixty-one per cent were concerned that aggressive price competition was
affecting research and technical development within firms as a way to cut
costs.
</TEXT>
