<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Way is cleared for Gold TV channel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK GOLD, the planned Pounds 30m television entertainment channel, now seems
certain to go ahead.
The new channel, which will be financed entirely by advertising, at least in
the first year, will be broadcast by the Astra satellite system.
A US television company has agreed in principle to underwrite the 65 per
cent of the equity not held by the channel's founders, Thames Television and
BBC Enterprises, the commercial arm of the BBC.
A deal being finalised with the unnamed company clears the way for a launch
of UK Gold in mid November. Thames, which will cease to be an ITV company at
the end of this year, will take a 15 per cent stake in the company, with an
option for a further 5 per cent, and the BBC will have 20 per cent.
The aim is for the rest of the equity to be held by four or five
shareholders, but the underwriting deal means that the launch of the channel
can now go ahead before all the shareholders are formally in place.
The channel, drawing on the programme libraries of Thames, the BBC and other
broadcasters, will be entirely devoted to entertainment. There will be no
news, current affairs, sport or religious programmes. The programme
schedules will include popular drama series, such as The Bill, and
Eastenders, and comedies such as Porridge.
A long-term programme deal has already been signed by BBC Enterprises and
another with Thames will be complete within a few days. The programmes will
be made available under existing agreements with Equity, the actors' union.
The Independent Television Commission has indicated that UK Gold's structure
is likely to be acceptable under the terms of the Broadcasting Act, which
prevents the BBC being part of an ITC-licensed satellite channel. The BBC
would be part of the UK Gold holding company but would not be part of a
separate company that would hold the licence.
ITV is still considering the possibility of launching a similar channel,
ITV2, using its programme library. It is not clear whether ITV2 is anything
more than an attempted spoiler.
UK Gold's business plan suggests that it will initially get a 3 per cent
share of viewing in homes that can receive satellite and cable television,
rising to 5 per cent in six or seven years. Executives privately suggest
that it may get 7 per cent or 8 per cent.
Although UK Gold is seen as primarily an advertising channel, it may join
one subscription packages of programmes now being planned for satellite
television. Although UK Gold will be on a Europe-wide satellite, it will be
available only in the UK because of restrictions in programme rights.
</TEXT>
