FT  21 SEP 92 / Service costs for offices increased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SERVICE charges for office buildings increased faster than inflation last
year, according to a report by Jones Lang Wootton, the chartered surveyor
and international property consultant.
Service charges now represent a larger share of tenants' gross costs as
rental levels continue to fall.
The report, which covers buildings ranging from 3,000 sq ft to 400,000 sq
ft, says the level of service charges last year reflected contract prices
agreed in 1990 that had not been influenced by the recession.
Jones Lang Wootton estimates that service charges this year will be at or
below the average level of inflation as contractors submit increasingly
competitive tenders.
Insurance costs rose an average of 10 per cent last year and are expected to
rise by a further 10 per cent this year in the face of 'uncertainty in the
insurance market for commercial property'.
The report says service charges accounted for 9.1 per cent of tenants' gross
costs last year for air-conditioned buildings in the West End of London
compared with 7.8 per cent in 1990, and 7.9 per cent in 1989. In the City,
the share of gross costs represented by service charges jumped to 12.5 per
cent in 1991 from 8.9 per cent in 1990 and 7 per cent in 1989.
Office Service Charge Analysis and Research. Jones Lang Wootton, 22 Hanover
Square, London W1A 2BN.
