<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Property advisers' skills criticised
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPERTY advisers lack proper management skills and financial expertise,
according to a report by the College of Estate Management, an independent
training and research establishment.
The report, based on 23 interviews with representatives from all sides of
the property industry, identifies weaknesses among property advisers,
including poor analytical skills; a reluctance to be innovative and
independent; and a tendency to be superficial. Advisers' strengths are
centred on contacts, local knowledge and depth of resources.
The report says that the failure of chartered surveyors to understand their
clients' overall business needs has led to the entry of other professions
such as accountants and management consultants into the marketplace.
Quantity surveyors, architects and building surveyors are declining in
importance because of changing practices in the building industry, the
report says. For instance, the growing importance of comprehensive 'design
and build' contracts has weakened demand for architects' traditional
management and co-ordination roles, although their design skills continue to
be in demand.
Demand for investment surveyors is also likely to fall, as their skills do
not meet the demands of increasingly complex financial markets.
In general, the professionals who will be at a disadvantage are those who
have 'a narrow, myopic outlook and training and an inability to bridge
across disciplines and understand both the complexity of, and synergy
within, the entire property and construction industry'.
The report concludes: 'Individuals need to be complete business men or
women, rather than narrow technicians.'
The Skills Mismatch. Publications Department, College of Estate Management,
White-knights, Reading, RG6 2AW. Pounds 20.
</TEXT>
