<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Mandarins turn their attention to a question of cash:
Economists are divided over ways of monitoring money supply
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WITH Britain likely to be in no hurry to rejoin the European exchange rate
mechanism, Treasury mandarins will be working overtime this week answering
an important question: what is the best way of monitoring the money supply?
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, gave a clear hint yesterday that the
supply of money - an important indicator of demand and inflationary
pressures - would have a bigger role in determining the direction of base
rates, which many politicians and industrialists would like to see brought
down quickly from 10 per cent.
The chancellor's comments will be both a relief and a challenge to
monetarist economists. While many have been angered by the progressively
smaller importance accorded to monetary targeting during the late 1980s,
they also find it difficult to agree on precisely which measure of the money
supply provides the best method of monitoring demand.
Professor Patrick Minford, a monetarist economist at Liverpool University
and long-time opponent of the ERM, said Britain should make M0 - a narrow
measure of money, which mainly comprises notes and coins in circulation, the
best known form of 'ready money' - the centrepiece of its targeting policy.
Prof Minford believes demand is so weak that Britain could safely cut base
rates to as little as 4 per cent without causing the pound to drift too low
or triggering an unpalatable rise in inflation.
In the opposing camp are other monetarists, including Professor Tim Congdon,
economic adviser to discount house Gerrard &amp; National, who says greater
weight should be given to targeting broad measures of the money supply.
Such measures comprise not only cash in circulation but monetary deposits.
Those can be drawn on for purchasing goods and services, and so provide an
additional representation of demand. Of those measures, the best known is
M4, which is cash in circulation plus sterling deposits in banks and
building societies.
Somewhere between devotees of 'broad' and 'narrow' money are economists
including Mr Peter Spencer, chief economist at Kleinwort Benson, the
investment house. Mr Spencer favours an eclectic measure of money which he
calls 'divisia money'. It accounts for cash together with monetary deposits
in banks and other institutions, with the amount of money in the deposits
given a 'weight', depending on the degree to which they represent ready
money as opposed to funds being kept to gain interest.
Under Mr Spencer's system, for example, current accounts in banks - which
many people draw on virtually all the time for purchases and so have a big
effect on the rest of the economy - would be given a weight of close to 100
per cent. Many kinds of savings deposits, on the other hand, would be given
a zero weighting because the owners of such money have little or no imminent
intention of releasing it into wider circulation.
In the early 1980s, Britain used a range of methods to target the money
supply. Sir Terry Burns, formerly the government's chief economic adviser,
who is now Treasury permanent secretary, was brought into Whitehall in 1980
primarily because he favoured monetary targeting.
But since the mid 1980s, monetary targeting has become a much less important
part of UK economic policymaking, with the Treasury switching instead after
ERM entry nearly two years ago to a full-blown method of targeting the
exchange rate.
The Treasury still formally targets M0, saying it should ideally be growing
at between zero and 4 per cent a year to keep the economy ticking over at
optimum level. In the year to the end of August, M0 grew 2.4 per cent,
indicating a continuation of a slack economy. However, the Bank of England
has always been sceptical about the value of M0 and has been more keen on
broad-money targeting. One UK official said recently that M0 targeting had
little practical relevance to steering the economy and had been kept mainly
'for presentational reasons'.
Assuming the Treasury can agree with the Bank precisely which monetary
measures to target, it will then probably try to decide on the target range,
a far from easy job.
It was the continual need to revise money targets - because of problems in
working out the link between specific measures of the money supply and
inflation - that led Mr Nigel Lawson, the former chancellor, in the mid
1980s to drop money targeting as a central plank of economic policy.
Mr Giles Keating, economics director at Credit Suisse First Boston, the
Swiss bank, said that, given the government's need to build up credibility
with financial markets after the debacle of the ERM suspension, the Treasury
should provide a 'clear statement' about the precise form its monetary
targeting should take. He said: 'The Treasury should publish some definite
rules about what it has in mind. It will not be enough to make some vague
promise about the government from now on taking into account monetary
aggregates.'
If the government follows Mr Keating's suggestion, the UK will follow many
other European governments in having explicit targets for the money supply.
The wheel would then have turned full circle for Sir Terry, who would find
official government thinking on the need to monitor this variable back to
what was the Treasury line 12 years ago.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
