<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / New fear of travel collapses sparked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MASON International Travel, a Scottish holiday company, has ceased trading
amid fears that more travel operators are facing collapse in the wake of
sterling's devaluation.
The Civil Aviation Authority said yesterday that five international travel
operators had ceased trading in the last month.
Mr Nigel Griffiths, Labour consumer affairs spokesman, claimed that last
week's devaluation had 'plunged holiday companies into financial crisis'. He
said travel operators would find that the money they had taken from clients
would no longer cover their bills abroad, because devaluation had increased
costs by 10 per cent.
Mason International Travel, based in Glasgow, specialised in package
holidays to Canada and the US. All its holidays were covered by bonds with
the Association of British Travel Agents (Abta) and the CAA.
The 300 customers estimated to be abroad will be able to continue their
holidays, while those with advance bookings will receive a full refund.
Mason International Travel traded under several names including Canada Air
Holidays, Canada By Design, America By Design, Florida By Design and Albany
Tours. It is believed that the company is seeking a buyer as a going
concern. A recorded message at its Glasgow offices yesterday reported that
it was temporarily closed but was 'hoping for good news by Tuesday'.
Mr Griffiths claimed that about 1m package holidays a year were taken with
non-Abta companies with none of the protection of Abta bonding.
EC law would require all travel companies to be bonded from January 1 next
year, Mr Griffiths said, but UK law offered no protection to holidaymakers
booking between now and December 31.
The government had already missed its deadline for issuing guidance on
implementation of the regulations, Mr Griffiths said. The Department of
Trade and Industry had previously told the travel trade that the bonding
regulations would be published on August 1.
Mr Griffiths accused the government of dithering and failing to take action.
'This gross negligence cost 40,000 holidaymakers their money and their
holidays when Land Travel collapsed without bonding in July,' he said.
He called on the government to publish the guidance regulations today and to
take action this week to enforce bonding on all travel companies to bridge
the gap between now and the end of the year.
