<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / World Economy and Business Review (5): More emphasis on
market forces - A look at the results of economic reform in Latin American
countries / The March of Western values
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE disintegration of the Soviet bloc has brought predictable claims of a
victory for the western style of democratic government and economic
management. But even before the discrediting of communism transformed the
map of the world, shifts towards more democratic systems of government and
more market-friendly economic systems were already under way in many
developing countries.
For pragmatic rather than ideological reasons, many governments had already
come to the conclusion that in a capital-scarce world, the market should
have a more important role in allocating resources than they had conceded
hitherto. There have been two main aspects to this change: the first has
involved attaining equilibrium in government finances; the second a series
of reforms to the structure of economies to make them more responsive to
market forces.
In Latin America, for example, the onset of the debt crisis 10 years ago
laid bare the economic mismanagement of military governments across the
region and paved the way for their replacement by elected successors. But,
also as a result of the crisis, governments found it impossible to raise
capital. Because their ability to sell debt was severely limited, any
attempt to stimulate the economy directly by increasing government spending
in excess of revenues has had one result: inflation. Thus reforms were
considered necessary to redirect the role of government, raising revenues by
restructuring tax systems and cutting expenditures by slimming down bloated
bureaucracies and privatising state industries.
Privatisation has had an important role in structural reform, too, as part
of a set of changes to allow for greater play of market forces. It has been
accompanied by a removal of quotas, tariffs and other obstacles to foreign
trade and reforms to improve the attraction of investment, domestic and
foreign.
Yet there is no doubt that governments have been reinforced in their
decision to throw out the state-dominated, inward-looking model of economic
development by the changes in eastern Europe. Graphic television pictures of
life in the former socialist countries have changed the point of view of
many voters. 'We used to think there were two ways we could develop our
economy. Now we realise that in the east, they live as badly as we do,' said
Mr Jaime Duran, a political analyst in Ecuador, where a government pledging
economic reforms has just assumed power.
This 'unipolar' world has exciting potential, particularly in the prospects
offered of a reduction in defence expenditures in developed and developing
countries. It has also meant in theory that governments in industrialised
countries can alter the basis of their relations with developing countries;
that aid can be used to bolster democracy and weaken tyranny, instead of
shoring up corrupt regimes whose only claim for support was opposition to
Moscow.
However, there is also disquiet in the developing world. Donor governments
have felt less reticent about imposing new, less ostensibly economic,
conditions on aid. The freedom of the US and its allies to intervene in
areas of the world in pursuit of domestic policy aims - such as combating
drug traffickers or securing oil supplies - is much enlarged.
Furthermore, without strong ideological competition, there is the danger of
drift in international policy-making, of purposelessness and petty squabbles
among the rich countries, epitomised by the inability to reach a conclusion
to the Uruguay round of free trade talks. Many policy-makers in developing
countries are thus worried that their unilateral decisions to open their
economies to the outside world will be greeted by growing protectionism in
the industrialised world.
Internally, economic reform has been no panacea for governments. While in
some countries - such as Mexico and Argentina - it has so far proved popular
and helped incumbent governments, in others, there has been a tension
between economic reform and the survival of democracy. In Venezuela, for
example, the government's reform programme, in spite of its relatively
modest scale, has been the focus of public demonstrations since a failed
army coup attempt last February. In Peru - a lesson for those who believe
left-wing revolutionaries have lost their potential to influence events - a
group of brutal Maoists threaten the state. Indeed, the most successful
economic reform movements in Latin America - Chile's of the 1980s and
Mexico's - have been pushed forward by two of the continent's least
democratic regimes.
Even in countries where reform has so far proved successful, there are
risks. Argentina's future development, for example, depends crucially on
stimulating its low levels of investment. And if the investment arrives in
Argentina, it is unlikely to arrive in all the countries that are
simultaneously opening their economies in the hope of stimulating
investment.
Amid such competition, aid practitioners are despondent about the ability of
much of Africa to attract meaningful amounts of private capital. Without
that, and with increased competition for western aid from eastern Europe,
the prospects for much of that continent appear dim. Furthermore, even if it
arrives, foreign investment may be perceived as exploitative, providing
potential problems for incumbent governments.
There are other areas where the market does not provide a complete answer or
where government will continue to have to play a significant role. In most
developing countries, raising capital for large project investments or for
small businesses is problematic, and in most there is a pressing need for
infrastructure investments. There is also a requirement for government
investment in sectors such as education: low wages are no longer, if they
ever were, a sufficient incentive for foreign investment, and an educated
workforce is an important draw for potential investors. As a decade of
austerity, the 1980s saw mounting social pressures in many developing
economies.
Another important development is the emergence of another value system which
has met with unmatched success over the past 20 years: that of Asia. While
the models offered by Japan and its Asian neighbours differ in detail, they
all place government at the centre of the development process. Japan is
growing in importance as a giver of aid and a provider of finance to the
multilateral institutions; Korea and Taiwan, once recipients of aid, are
themselves becoming donors. Meanwhile, the relative weight of the US economy
and the importance of the US as an aid donor continues to decline.
The disintegration of the Soviet bloc may in some countries be accompanied
by the simultaneous strengthening of democracy and the market economy. In
others, there will be tension or conflict between the two. In any event, the
hypothesis that the world is on the verge of an uncontested victory for
'western' values must be considered distinctly far-fetched.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
