<DOCNO>FT923-1922</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIUDDAAYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920921
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Maastricht - The French Vote: Currencies to remain under
strain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EUROPEAN Exchange Rate Mechanism should now live at least another week,
if in a slimmer and weaker form. But the severe monetary strains within
Europe, which the French referendum campaign has highlighted, will not go
away and may intensify over the coming weeks and months.
Europe's finance ministers may have breathed a sigh of relief as early
reports suggested a narrow vote in favour of the treaty. The initial
reaction in the currency markets was muted, following the first exit poll,
suggesting that traders did not intend to test the resolve of the French
government to hold its parity with the D-Mark, at least for now. A No vote
would mean even greater turmoil during the course of today.
Two conclusions can be already be drawn from the events of the past week:
the era of the hard ERM involving almost all of Europe's currencies is over;
and a two-speed monetary regime is likely to persist for some months.
Two devaluations and two departures from the system over the past week have
broken the realignment taboo which has reigned since Italy realigned in
January of 1990. The events of the last week have demonstrated that when the
markets want a a weak currency to devalue there is little that the national
monetary authorities can do except acquiesce.
So it is far too early to tell whether or not there will be more
realignments within the ERM over the next few weeks. The peseta and the
Irish punt, along with the franc, remained near the bottom of their trading
bands at the end of last week.
Dealers may yet decide that Spain, like Italy and the UK last week, will not
be able to sustain its current high interest rate policy without a much
larger devaluation.
Both Italy and the UK appear to have decided they are better off outside the
ERM, at least for the time being, after the bruising and expensive events of
the last week. Both countries made it clear over the weekend that they would
not re-enter the system until German interest rates have fallen further.
But the great uncertainty is whether the ERM can survive at all as anything
more than a northern European greater D-Mark zone.
What matters most is the stability of the link between the franc and the
D-Mark. A No vote would almost certainly have meant a run on the franc and
probably a French devaluation or even withdrawal from the system. An
emphatic Yes vote might have meant a more rapid move to north European
monetary union.
But last night's marginal result resolves nothing. The closeness of the
French vote, and the uncertainty over whether the Maastricht ratification
process can be completed, make it doubtful whether the ERM will now evolve
into monetary union, at least for the foreseeable future.
Will the French elite be able, and the public willing, to tolerate more of
the same policy of high interest rates, high unemployment and slow growth
now that the goal of monetary union appears to have gone?
And would the increasingly friendless, but now more powerful, Bundesbank be
willing to support the franc if it does now come under pressure within the
ERM, something it was not willing to do for the lira or sterling last week?
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
