<DOCNO>FT923-1923</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIUDDAAXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920921
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Maastricht - The French Vote: Europe's future still clouded
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French endorsement of the Maastricht Treaty does not lift the cloud of
uncertainty over the future of the European Community; nor does it mean that
the path toward political and monetary union set out in the treaty will be
made easier.
But the prospect of a political crisis in France, which might have spread to
other European capitals, has been averted.
The French result does not resolve the many questions about Maastricht and
the concept of European Union which the 12 Member states signed up to in
December 1991. The narrowness of the verdict in France, the driving force
behind European integration since the 1957 Treaty of Rome, is certain to
encourage doubters elsewhere in Europe, particularly in Britain.
Indeed, last week's turmoil in the financial markets, which led to Britain
and Italy withdrawing from the Exchange Rate Mechanism, leaves the goal of
monetary union for the Twelve by the end of the century a remote goal
indeed.
The financial markets imposed this reality last week; France's lukewarm
support for Maastricht will not remove the doubts about the economic
feasibility of the enterprise, nor the impression of a 'two-speed Europe'
with the stronger currencies gathering inside a D-Mark bloc.
The French vote will encourage the French and German governments, along with
Mr Jacques Delors, the European Commission president, to press ahead as fast
as possible with ratification of the treaty elsewhere in Europe.
The drive for solidarity may be politically understandable; but it puts
Britain and Denmark - the two countries harbouring the most doubts about
Maastricht's merits - directly in the firing line.
The French vote poses numerous problems for Britain, which holds the
rotating six month-long presidency of the EC. French rejection would have
allowed Mr John Major, UK prime mInister, to call for European co-operation,
but in a looser, less centralised form than in the Maastricht Treaty.
Now Maastricht limps on, and a weakened Mr Major must decide whether to
hobble along too. He must not only deal with the Euro-sceptics in his own
Conservative party, he must also reckon with pressure from Paris and Bonn to
put the Maastricht bill before parliament as soon as possible in the
interest of the whole Community.
The Danes are taking their time, knowing that they need several months or
longer to prepare Danish public opinion for a a second referendum. A senior
EC official said last week that too much pressure on the Danish people could
backfire.
Last night, EC officials expressed confidence that the French vote, however
narrow, would restore a measure of confidence that the EC could manage its
own affairs and that it had a clear vision of its future. Thus, the 12 could
focus on the business at hand: the completion of the Single Market, the
Delors II package for funnelling new funds to the poorer southern states
such as Spain and Portugal; and, more tentatively, the aim of enlarging the
Community.
Last night, the mood in Brussels was relief mixed with contrition.
As Mr Karel van Miert, the Belgian commissioner responsible for the
environment, acknowledged that it is important for the European Community to
win back public opinion, to remove the feeling that Brussels is run by a
technocratic elite out of touch with ordinary people in Europe.
The implication is that Brussels has learnt its lessons from the Danish and
French referendums and is ready, in some as yet unspecified way, to make
amends.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 3
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-1924</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIUDDAAWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920921
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Maastricht - The French Vote: Dilemma for Major as UK doubts
grow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS good for Europe and good for Britain. But that is not to say it is
good for the government.
That judgment, offered by a British minister last night on the Yes vote in
France for the Maastricht treaty, encapsulates the dilemma now facing Mr
John Major.
When the British prime minister was asked in the wake of last week's
sterling crisis whether he still hoped that the French would endorse the
treaty, he replied in the affirmative. But there was no enthusiasm in his
voice. It was the same last night as he offered his congratulations to
President Francois Mitterrand.
It is not hard to explain the ambivalence.
There is much in the treaty that Mr Major wants to preserve. He sees the
inter-governmental dimension which it adds to the Treaty of Rome and the
Single European Act as the route to Europe's future - and to Britain's
participation in that future.
There was serious concern in Whitehall that a No vote would have been
followed immediately by a new Franco-German initiative to secure European
Union for an inner core of EC nations - underlining Britain's retreat to the
fringe, after last's week enforced withdrawal of sterling from the ERM.
But Mr Major must also look to domestic politics, where Maastricht threatens
to re-open the wounds which led his party into civil war only two years ago
and prompted it to ditch Baroness Thatcher.
Pressing ahead with ratification will greatly compound the political
difficulties triggered by sterling's ignominious departure from the ERM.
After the debacle on the currency markets, the Tory Euro-sceptics have
gained new confidence - and many new recruits among the previously
uncommitted. They are promising a bloody campaign against any move to return
sterling to the ERM and against Maastricht ratification.
Mr Major, who has spent the past two years rebuilding a pro-European
coalition in his party, is seriously weakened. His demeanour over the past
few days points also to disillusionment.
Cabinet colleagues believe that will be a temporary phenomenon: when Mr
Major considers coolly the options, he will conclude as he did two years ago
that there is no place for Britain on the periphery of Europe. It may take
time.
The official message from Whitehall last night was that in its capacity as
president of the Community, Britain would now press ahead with the task of
securing ratification by the Twelve. But no one should expect too much too
quickly.
The narrowness of the French vote and evidence across the Community that its
citizens are restless with the pace of integration are seen in London as
demanding a thorough re-assessment by its leaders of the Community's
ambitions.
The expectation is that the emergency summit of EC leaders early next month
will consider how the voters of Europe can be reassured that Maastricht does
not represent the increased centralisation of power in Brussels.
The British Foreign Office has been working on plans to give substance to
the idea of 'subsidiarity', or decentralisation, enshrined only in outline
in the treaty.
The summit needs also to co-ordinate a response to Denmark's assessment of
the clarifications and changes it would need to persuade its electorate to
reverse the rejection of the treaty in a June referendum. The aim is to
secure a framework agreement with Copenhagen at the Edinburgh summit in
December.
More controversially, Mr Major wants the leaders to undertake a detailed
examination of the ERM - and in particular of the 'asymmetry' which loads
the burden of responsibility for defending existing parities on the
governments and central banks of weak currencies.
Those with longer memories in Whitehall have few illusions that the
Bundesbank - which Mr Major blames for sterling's collapse - would be
willing to compromise its independence. It has rejected too often demands
from France and Italy that in times of crisis it must share the cost of
intervention and demonstrate willingness to cut its interest rates.
But Mr Major's domestic politics demand that he uses the presidency to put
the issue at the top of the EC agenda.
As for ratification of the treaty, the best that the rest of Europe can hope
from its presidency is that the House of Commons will be asked again to vote
in principle on the issue later in the autumn.
Detailed consideration of the legislation will have to wait until next year.
Mr Major's oft-repeated aspiration to keep Britain at the heart of Europe
remains on hold.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
