<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Maastricht - The French Vote: Winners and losers in the
French campaigns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE biggest gamble of President Francois Mitterrand's career looked set to
succeed by a small margin last night, but it has been a costly victory on
both the European and domestic scene.
As expected, the initial returns indicated the French electorate had
approved the Maastricht treaty on European monetary and political union by a
whisker, with a 51-51.5 per cent majority in favour of the treaty on an
unusually high 70 per cent turn-out, according to exit polls.
The French electorate flirted with the unthinkable, and it was only after
intense campaigning from national political leaders of all parties and
several European heads of government that they shrank back from the brink at
the last minute and voted for the treaty.
Yet the project has already been battered, as has the reputation of many of
those who sought to save it. Maastricht had already suffered perhaps
irreversible damage from last week's currency crisis. Now it has received
only grudging approval from one of Europe's two main pillars.
A Yes under these circumstances can hardly be read as a boon to European
integration. On the contrary, it confirms that the pace of European
construction will now go ahead more slowly and cautiously.
Last night's result could also introduce a chill into France's relations
with Germany, whose leaders have had to swallow their irritation in recent
weeks as both Yes and No campaigners have played on fears of German
domination to bolster their cases. The Franco-German alliance is intact, but
weakened by the doubts exposed during campaign.
The other important lesson driven home by yesterday's referendum is that the
French political establishment is out of touch with a large part of the
electorate. Sensitive to this, the current Socialist government has already
promised that European matters will be debated more thoroughly in the
National Assembly.
When Mr Mitterrand called a referendum in early June, he knew he would spark
off an intense debate. Indeed, he claims to have welcomed the opportunity
for the French to have its first in-depth debate on Europe for four decades.
Yet the government gave the impression, by starting off its campaign on an
easy-going, if not complacent, footing, of having no idea of the sheer
strength of the opposition to Maastricht. The other Yes campaigners, the
RPR, the centre-right UDF and the Generation Ecologie, also had to work far
harder than they imaged to get the Yes vote into the bag.
But the strength of opposition to Maastricht was not the only surprise to
come from the French campaign. It also unearthed general anxiety about the
costs and obligations of European Community members, from agricultural
policy reform to industrial competition, plus widespread provincial
resentment of the Parisian governing class.
So where do the main players stand in the wake of last night's marginal Yes
vote?
Mr Mitterrand can claim that his authority is just about intact, even if his
illness casts uncertainty over how long he will be able to stay.
Former president Mr Valery Giscard d'Estaing, president of the UDF, one of
the two main opposition rivals to succeed Mr Mitterrand, has emerged
strengthened from his part in the Yes campaign.
Mr Giscard d'Estaing's main opposition rival, Mr Jacques Chirac, president
of the Gaullist RPR, has been weakened by supporting Maastricht when most of
his party oppose the treaty. Yet the campaign has also showed that the RPR
has no other leader capable of handling - even if not reconciling - its
internal splits.
The leading anti-Maastricht RPR rebels, Mr Philippe Seguin and Mr Charles
Pasqua, both ended their campaigns admitting that Mr Chirac was the RPR's
best potential presidential candidate.
The outcome of all this is that the two right-wing parties, which have
agreed to choose a single presidential candidate, are now very likely to
field a pro-Maastricht leader - either Mr Giscard d'Estaing or Mr Chirac -
for the next presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
