<DOCNO>FT923-1931</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIUDDAAPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920921
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Maastricht - The French Vote: Delors hails 'strong
foundation' for union
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JACQUES Delors, president of the European Commission, last night welcomed
the French vote as giving a strong foundation to moves towards closer
European monetary and political union.
Speaking in Paris, he said: 'May they (French voters) be thanked for France,
for Europe, for democracy, for progress, for history.'
'The fact that the French have ratified by a direct process gives a stronger
foundation to the legitimate construction of Europe, even though it is
necessary to take account of the fears and anxieties of those who have voted
No,' he said.
Mr Delors, who had threatened to resign if the French had rejected the
treaty, also hit back at accusations of over-centralisation levelled at the
Commission by opponents of the treaty.
He said: 'It is the Council of Ministers and representatives of the 12
governments who must explain Europe in each country.'
Other European leaders reacted with immediate relief to the French approval
of the Maastricht Treaty, echoing Mr Delors' reaffirmation that the project
of a deeper, broader and politically united Europe remained on course.
However, approval of the French referendum result among EC governments was
tinged with concern at the narrowness of the outcome and apprehension about
the prospects for ratification of the treaty elsewhere in the Community,
notably in Britain.
Mr Helmut Kohl, the German chancellor, said that despite the narrowness of
the vote, the result was a 'new boost' for Europe and pledged to work on
expanding the EC. 'Along with the deepening of the Community, we want in the
next few years to realise the second great goal of our European policy
quickly: that is the expansion of the future union with the Efta (European
Free Trade Association) states that have applied for membership,' he said.
Mr Kohl said he was sure that Germany would ratify the Maastricht Treaty
before the end of the year.
Other German leaders nevertheless cautioned that the narrow vote gave cause
for reflection. Mr Klaus Kinkel, the German foreign minister, while calling
the vote a 'decisive step forward', cautioned that 'we must, however, think
over a few things'.
His warning was echoed by Mr Theo Waigel, the German finance minister, who
said that 'a narrow majority is significantly better than a narrow minority,
but added that the margin was 'no cause for triumph'.
Mr Jack Lang, the French education minister who co-ordinated the Socialist
government's Yes campaign, hailed victory minutes after the first computer
projections indicated voters had approved the treaty.
'I am proud that a majority of the French people have chosen Europe. It is a
victory for France, a victory for Europe,' he said.
However, leaders of the No campaign were equally quick to focus on the
narrow margin of the vote. 'It's a pseudo-success, a mediocre Yes,' said Mr
Jean-Marie Le Pen, leader of the National Front.
The European architects of the Maastricht Treaty immediately greeted the
French approval with strong declarations that momentum towards European
unity had been sustained.
Mr Giuliano Amato, the Italian prime minister, said he 'breathed a sigh of
relief' at the likely Yes result. 'If the French electorate had not voted
Yes, the work of 40 years would probably have been undone, causing
irreparable damage,' he said.
However, Mr Piet Dankert, the Dutch deputy foreign minister, described his
reaction as 'sombre'. He told Dutch television that 'the problem is that it
is a very small majority, and does not get us in the clear.'
He said the treaty still faced stern tests in Britain, where it must be
ratified by the House of Commons, and in Denmark, where a referendum has
already rejected the treaty.
Mr Karel van Miert, a member of the European Commission, also sounded a
pessimistic note, saying 'the damage has been done'. He said he was worried
that the Community was 'drifting apart and losing credibility'. He said:
'When things start sliding, it is difficult to stop them.'
Denmark, which voted against the Maastricht Treaty in a referendum in June,
hoped that the Yes vote would help it persuade other EC members countries to
accept its need for special arrangements with the EC, Mr Uffe
Ellemann-Jensen, the Danish foreign minister, said last night.
'We could be very difficult for the other countries, but we have to ask
ourselves whether this would be clever,' he said.
'I think it should now be easier for Denmark to obtain a special arrangement
with the European Community,' he said. 'The European landscape today is
totally different from what it was in early June.'
Speaking in Paris, Mr Delors reasserted his belief that monetary union
should happen as quickly as possible. 'What happened on the exchange markets
a week ago was due to the absence of real and effective consultation between
the major currencies.'
He said the difference between US and German interest rates was also to
blame.
But 'that doesn't mean to say that the European monetary system is useless.
On the contrary. But under those circumstances economies which are not the
healthiest suffer,' he said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
