<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / Maastricht - The French Vote: A battle is won, but not yet
the war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
  By DAVID GARDNER and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE'S narrow endorsement of Maastricht was greeted with almost cathartic
relief in Brussels, and calls for the Community to redouble efforts to
secure economic, monetary and political union. But most officials recognised
that what had been won in France was a battle, not the war.
Quite apart from whether Danish voters can be persuaded to reverse last
June's rejection of Maastricht, concern is growing in Brussels about whether
Mr John Major, the British prime minister, can get the UK parliament to
ratify the treaty, after the government's humiliating defeat on sterling
policy last week.
In a direct reference to Britain, a senior Commission official said 'one
problem we can solve, but not two - especially if it is the UK.'
'The (British) problem was there even before we had the referendum,' said
Belgium's commissioner, Mr Karel Van Miert. But asked whether the UK could
be the next weak link in the Maastricht chain, he said: 'I tend to believe
that is the case.'
Mr Van Miert was cautious about the immediate future. 'I think everyone has
a clear impression about how much damage has been done over the last few
weeks,' he said. 'The first task is to stop the drift apart in the Community
from worsening.'
Officials in Brussels expect the meetings today of EC foreign ministers at
the UN in New York, and EC finance ministers attending the International
Monetary Fund meeting in Washington, to extract every bit of momentum they
can from yesterday's vote. Nevertheless, they expected it would require an
emergency summit within the next month to get Maastricht really back on
track.
Officials last night in Brussels took comfort, however, in the renewed
possibilities of a Gatt world trade agreement opened by the French Yes.
They confirmed that the final push to unblock the Uruguay Round trade talks,
hung up on EC-US inability to agree how far to cut farm subsidies, would now
go ahead in an attempt to reach agreement before the US presidential
election on November 3.
The French vote gives us 'new arguments for a compromise', one official
said. France's reluctance to make farm subsidy concessions before the
referendum was what made impossible a settlement at July's summit of the
Group of Seven big industrial nations in Munich.
Despite last week's turmoil in the currency markets, senior officials argued
strongly last night that Mastricht's goal of monetary union remained intact,
thanks to the French vote.
Germany's senior commissioner, Mr Martin Bangemann, said it is 'quite clear
that only Emu (economic and monetary union) can bring an end to speculation
and that kind of situation in the markets.'
Brushing aside the rancour in the UK over the German Bundesbank's role in
last week's events, Mr Bangemann insisted that Emu promised 'one currency
defended by one central bank in Europe, with one desire to defend stability,
but looking after the European situation and not just one country's'
Nonetheless, his colleague, Mr Van Miert, conceded that political as well as
economic difficulties surrounding Maastricht meant that 'more bilateralism
and more of two speeds' could make it difficult to keep the 12 together.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
