<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / World Economy and Business Review (2): A middle-class gap -
The former Soviet empire has inherited an outmoded feudal system which is
proving a difficult starting point for a modern, free-enterprise economy /
The Communist Legacy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NO ECONOMIST has described the problem of converting communist societies to
capitalism better than Mr Lech Walesa, the Polish president. 'It is like
trying to make a fish out of fish soup,' he once observed. But that is the
kind of inchoate broth that the peoples of the former Soviet empire
inherited from decades of an all too successful experiment in Stalinist
social engineering.
For most of the 20th Century the Soviet world was sealed off from the rapid
technological change which created unprecedented wealth and transformed the
social and institutional structures of capitalist societies. Instead of an
expanding, self-confident, property-owning middle class, the Soviet model
re-created outmoded feudal relationships.
At the heart of the economic problems confronting the new post-communist
governments is the lack of a middle class and the economic and other
institutions and attitudes connected with it. The all-powerful party state
was served by varying ranks of propertyless state serfs. Instead of a
naturally evolving middle class, the Soviet system left behind the
nomenklatura.
This party-selected, and therefore dependent, elite managed the system and
ran the militarised command economy. In the name of the party its servants
eliminated or subverted pre-existing political, civil, religious and
economic institutions, perverting memory and re-writing history as they did
so.
It is hardly surprising under these unpromising circumstances that the task
of building capitalism is proving more complicated than those who had little
previous awareness of communist regimes thought, especially in the first
flush of enthusiasm which accompanied the collapse of the Berlin Wall and
the disintegration of the Soviet state.
The surprise is the extent of transformation already achieved in central
Europe, where the Soviet system was in place for only 45 years, and the
determination with which market reformers are pressing ahead, in spite of
growing opposition from the old managerial and other elites, in Russia and
other Soviet republics where even the memory of capitalism had been largely
eliminated.
The problems caused by the lack of a middle and entrepreneurial class help
to explain why privatisation is at the heart of macro-economic strategies
throughout the former Soviet empire. The crucial sub-text of this mechanism
to transfer ownership from an amorphous state to private individuals and
companies, or foreign investors, is the consequent creation of an
entrepreneurial and proprietorial class with a stake in stability, and a
willingness to take decisions and bear responsibility.
Given the virtual absence of private capital, and the destruction of savings
through hyper-inflation, the privatisation process has perforce been
unconventional and imaginative. It is not easy to build capitalism without
capital. Hence the introduction of unprecedented coupon mass-privatisation
schemes pioneered by Czechoslovakia and Poland and watched with intense
interest by others, especially Russia and other newly-independent ex-Soviet
republics.
The pacemakers of reform are the central European countries of
Czechoslovakia, Hungary and Poland which were relatively developed
capitalist societies in the inter-war period. They all have association
agreements with the European Community and are striving to fulfil the
requirements for full-fledged EC entry by the turn of the century.
Czechoslovakia was on a par with Germany before the war, while Poland
managed to retain most of its agriculture in private hands and thus kept a
large, albeit disadvantaged, capitalist sector alive throughout the
communist period. Individual Poles also became black market traders on a
large scale and this entrepreneurial talent helped Poland to privatise the
former lumbering state distribution system with extraordinary speed after
the communist regime collapsed.
The most difficult task of re-education is faced by the newly-independent
former Soviet states. They were all part of an authoritarian, centralised
empire before they became involuntary 'builders of socialism' for over seven
decades. Some, like Ukraine or Belarus, are having to build an independent
state for the first time. Others, like Georgia and Armenia, are
resuscitating ancient kingdoms submerged for centuries.
This state-building process is taking place in parallel with the
reconstruction of economic ties on a market-orientated basis. It has to cope
with the distortions left behind by the artificial, politically motivated
integration of the former all-Union economy.
The penchant for building giant plants capable of supplying the entire
Soviet market from one or two factories, and receiving their inputs from
similar plants elsewhere in this far-flung empire, has made all the new
states dangerously vulnerable to supply disruptions.
Throughout this huge area extending over half of Europe and half of Asia
fledgling businessmen and politicians are having to learn basic economic
concepts such as private property, the law of supply and demand, marginal
utility, rent, cost and profit and amortisation. Fundamental capitalist
institutions such as banks, insurance companies, pension funds, building
societies, accountancy firms, advertising and marketing companies existed
only in a primitive form, if at all, and are having to be created from the
ground up.
The unprecedented scale of the task is such that most of the effort and the
resources will have to come from those involved. Capital and know-how
injections are only forthcoming on a large scale in the specific and
untypical German case. The World Bank, the International Monetary Fund, the
specially created European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD),
have all made revealing studies and geared up to give modest financial
backing and technical support in key sectors.
But the main objective of the new regimes is to attract foreign equity
investment from companies prepared to inject their managerial skills and
integrate their new subsidiaries into their existing international
operations.
Until now little more than Dollars 5bn of equity capital has been invested
in the entire region since the old system collapsed in 1989, a tiny fraction
of the overall capital flows into south-east Asia or Latin America. But this
is only the beginning of a long process of development which will
fundamentally condition the shape of the 21st Century global economy.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-1937</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIUDDAAJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920921
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / World Economy and Business Review (7): Fiscal rhetoric
versus reality - Why the IMF is chiding the G7 / Public Spending and Debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN WOLF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Communique after communique from the Group of Seven leading industrial
countries has paid lip service to the cause of fiscal consolidation. But it
is naive to read leaders' lips. Action matters far more.
In April, for example, the G7 finance ministers and heads of government,
meeting in Washington, underlined 'the need to reduce fiscal deficits in all
countries with large budgetary imbalances through credible medium-term
consolidation strategies. This is important,' they went on, 'both for
countries with long-lasting fiscal imbalances and for countries experiencing
exceptional adjustment challenges.'
The IMF was more direct. In its World Economic Outlook of May 1992 it
recalled the 'consensus reached among industrial countries at the beginning
of the 1980s that medium-term objectives were best served by adhering to
anti-inflationary monetary policies, by reducing fiscal deficits (preferably
by restrictions on government spending rather than tax increases) and by
eliminating structural rigidities.
'Lack of success in this regard is,' complained the IMF, 'particularly
evident in the US and Italy, which both missed the opportunity to
consolidate their budgetary positions during the long period of sustained
growth in the 1980s. More recently, two countries that were relatively
successful . . . , namely Germany and . . . the UK, have experienced a shift
from fiscal balance (Germany) or budget surplus (the UK) to substantial
actual and projected fiscal imbalances.'
The IMF is entitled to wag its finger. According to OECD estimates, there
has been structural and not merely cyclical deterioration in the general
government budget balances of most OECD countries (see chart). But this
pattern must be set against the rather more favourable trends in public
finance during the 1980s.
First, the growth of public spending was brought under control. Between 1970
and 1980 the share of government outlays in the GDP of the G7 countries rose
from 32.3 per cent to 38.4 per cent. In OECD Europe it rose more sharply,
from 36.6 per cent to 46.0 per cent. These trends could not continue
forever. In the 1980s, they did not. Between 1980 and 1989, the share of
government outlays in GDP remained essentially unchanged in the G7 and rose
only slightly, from 46 per cent to 47.6 per cent, in OECD Europe.
Second, fiscal deficits improved. For the G7 the general government
financial deficit reached a peak of 4.3 per cent of GDP in 1983, falling to
0.9 per cent in 1989, before bouncing back a little, to 1.6 per cent, in
1990. The pattern for the OECD as a whole was similar.
Finally, although fiscal deficits did not shrink fast enough to prevent the
overall burden of net public debt from rising in the 1980s, that increase
was not dramatic. Between 1983 and 1991, the ratio of net public debt to GDP
rose from 28.4 to 32.0 per cent in the G7 and from 35.3 to 41.3 per cent in
Europe. But there were a few dramatic deteriorations: Italy's debt burden
rose from 68.8 per cent of GDP in 1983 to 99.6 per cent in 1991, Canada's
rose from 22.9 to 48.3 per cent and that of the US rose from 24.1 to 36.3
per cent. But Japan and the UK reduced their fiscal debt burdens.
Mixed success in the 1980s, followed by back-sliding during the slow down is
the reality behind the rhetoric of fiscal consolidation. What then are the
prospects for the fairly immediate future?
The US is likely to contribute little to consolidation in the near future,
whoever is elected president. Meanwhile, Japan has just committed itself to
a breath-taking piece of anti-consolidation. The Y10,700bn (Dollars 86m)
fiscal package announced at the end of August is the largest emergency
package in Japanese history, even as a percentage of gross national product.
Meanwhile, Europe remains rhetorically wedded to the orthodoxy of the 1980s.
Thus EC ministers emphasised at their meeting in Bath early this month 'the
importance of early and full implementation of strict convergence
programmes.'
That would mean severe pain in several member states, according to the
OECD's latest Economic Outlook. Implementation of the Maastricht criteria
for fiscal convergence - a 3 per cent target for the overall deficit of
general government and a 60 per cent target for the ratio of public debt to
GDP - could force substantial absolute reductions in public expenditure on
Italy, Belgium and Greece.
A leaked report from the IMF says that the belt-tightening required to meet
the Maastricht criteria would slow growth across the EC by 0.4 to 0.8
percentage points a year between 1993 and 1996. Whether the Maastricht
treaty is ratified or not, fiscal consolidation is likely to be less than
advertised in Europe, at least without a spontaneous recovery in economic
activity.
Fiscal austerity remains the slogan. The reality is, and will remain, rather
different.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-1938</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIUDDAAIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920921
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / World Economy and Business Review (8): Greener glow in
politics - The Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro marked the beginning of an
attempt to set global standards / Environment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECESSIONS are not auspicious for the environment: greenery becomes a luxury
when times are hard. Nonetheless, the environment has clearly moved up the
political agenda this year in spite of the economic stresses facing the
world.
The main reason is obviously the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in June at
which more than 100 heads of state solemnly committed themselves to a wide
range of environmental objectives.
President Mitterrand of France, for example, spoke of the need for a 'new
international order' which would combine disarmament, security, development
and respect for the environment.
Although it is still too early to gauge the full importance of Rio, the fact
that it was held at all and attracted such an impressive attendance ensured
it will have some impact. The question is: how much, and in what form? And
how will environmental considerations be balanced against other factors,
like the need to foster growth?
From the world economic viewpoint, Rio offered three broad themes.
One was the growing north-south divide, and the environmental degradation in
the third world that can be directly attributed to poverty. This, however,
is unlikely to have much immediate impact on policy-making. It was clear in
Rio that the rich industrial nations are heavily preoccupied with their own
problems, and are unwilling to make big financial commitments or trade
concessions to narrow the gap.
The second was growing acceptance of the need to get the world economy on to
a sustainable path, and stop consuming resources at the expense of future
generations.
To be effective, countries would have to start accounting for resources
which they regard as 'free', like air and water, or jacking up the price of
non-renewable resources to levels that make people realise they are being
depleted.
The third was in the area of practical measures to deal with threats to the
environment, in particular plant and animal life, and the climate. Two
treaties were agreed. One is aimed at encouraging reductions in emissions of
harmful gases believed to be causing global warming. But this had to be
watered down, because it was feared tough measures like curbs on oil
consumption or emission controls would smother economic growth. The other is
intended to control commercial exploitation of plant and animal life.
President Bush refused to sign this treaty, because he fears it will
undermine patent rights to medicines and other substances using natural
ingredients.
The third world came away from Rio disappointed. They were looking for more
financial or technological aid to help overcome their environmental
problems, but they left virtually empty-handed and, in many cases, angered
by demands that they stop chopping down their rain forests.
The industrial nations, on the other hand, made clear they had mixed
feelings about Rio. Their leaders were keen to stress concern for the
environment, but within strict limits dictated by the need not to damage
prospects for economic growth. Therefore, virtually no decisions were taken
that will have an immediate impact on the world economy.
Shortly after the event, Mr John Major, the UK prime minister, sent a Rio
checklist to his counterparts at the head of EC and OECD countries, urging
follow-through action. Among his proposals were deadlines to ratify Rio
treaties and come up with implementation plans, support for follow-up
machinery, and a timetable to set up the Commission on Sustainable
Development, which is to be the UN body charged with ensuring that Rio
decisions are respected.
Rio has not changed anything overnight, but it has shown that environmental
factors will have to be built more fully into economic decision-making. It
drove home the message that resources are finite, and that many
environmental issues, such as those affecting the atmosphere and water, have
become matters of global rather than just national concern.
For many countries, particularly the more developed, this was only a matter
of reinforcing a message that had already been taken on board. But it is
probably true to say that Rio marked the beginning of an attempt to set
global environmental standards, and that these will evolve during the 1990s.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
