<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / World Economy and Business Review (10): A humbling
experience - The monetary excesses of the 1980s are costing the country dear
/ Japan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVEN BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT HAS been a humbling year for financial authorities in Tokyo. For most of
1992, government economists and Bank of Japan officials insisted that the
Japanese economy was suffering from little more than a hard-to-explain bout
of self-doubt.
True, land and stock prices were plummeting as a result of a tight money
policy. But all calculations appeared to show that with the employment
market tight, and consumers flush with cash, brisk consumer demand would
keep a firm floor under the economy.
In the end, amid mounting signs of a financial crisis, the calculations
proved false, and the government was forced to step in at the end of August
with the largest emergency economic package in Japanese history, amounting
to Y10,700bn.
The action followed a rising fear that Japan may be passing quickly from a
Japanese-style slowdown into a full-blown American-style recession, with
several quarters of negative economic growth and significant unemployment.
What has gone wrong? In simple terms, Japan is paying a huge price for the
monetary excesses of the late 1980s, when record low interest rates prompted
a fantastic rise in stock and land prices. The Bank of Japan, under strong
international pressure at the time to cut Japan's trade surplus, held the
official discount rate to 2.5 per cent for more than 2 1/2 years to
stimulate imports.
This it did, temporarily, but the action led to asset and consumer price
inflation and an overheated economy. The Bank of Japan moved to squeeze the
money supply in 1989, and land and stock prices have fallen spectacularly.
It appeared until early this year, however, that the central bank had
managed to isolate financial and asset markets from the rest of the economy.
In retrospect, the sharp fluctuations in interest rates had set up the
country's mainstream manufacturing sector for a severe cyclical crash.
Vehicle and electronics companies took advantage of the historic low cost of
capital to raise financing. Indeed, they were frequently able to issue
convertible bonds in the stock market for 1 per cent or less, and earn a
higher return by depositing the money in the bank.
With capital cheap, and consumers spending money lavishly, it was natural
for companies to expand capacity, and private capital spending rose by more
than 10 per cent for four years running.
The spending, which had been a principal source of economic growth, however,
could not be sustained when the cost of capital began to rise. As a result
demand growth started to slow. As new plant opened, inventories piled up.
This in itself was enough to hurt profits badly, but it came at a time when
the bill for the binge of capital spending in terms of depreciation charges
was mounting heavily on profit and loss accounts.
The reaction has been to introduce further cuts in capital spending, which
led to a sharper contraction in demand. The Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan
estimates that total capital investment will be off 0.1 per cent in fiscal
1992, with manufacturing investment off by 8.7 per cent.
Japan's trusty consumers were supposed to prevent the situation from getting
out of hand by continuing to spend freely. This, the theory went, was
because of a structural labour shortage. In the end, however, Japanese
companies have been cutting overtime work, limiting bonus payments, and
reducing hiring. Bankruptcies of small manufacturing companies have been
rising. As a result, household income is not so secure after all.
All measures of consumer spending have turned downward. Department store
sales have shown a year-on-year decline for five consecutive months to July.
In August, new car sales plunged 18.6 per cent.
With capital investment and consumer spending accounting for 65 per cent of
Japan's gross national product, and both stagnating, there appears little
chance of the government coming anywhere close to its original growth target
of 3.5 per cent for the fiscal year ending March 1993. Many private
economists now believe growth will slip below 2 per cent, even with the
emergency spending package and its headline figure of Y10,700bn, which comes
to 2.3 per cent of GNP.
Only about half of the advertised total will contribute directly to GNP
growth, as this is pure spending for public works or housing. The balance
includes acquisition of land and a variety of loan programmes which, given
the weak state of demand, may or may not be taken up fully. The impact of
the package will not be felt until the new year.
As important as the extra spending measures, was the promise from the
government that a programme would be put in place to help banks get bad
loans off their books. These bad loans may now total Y25,000bn to Y30,000bn,
although no one knows the exact size. The cost of bearing so much bad debt
had wiped out bank profits and forced banks to sell securities to dress up
the accounts, thus further depressing the stock market and undermining the
capital base of the banks.
This, more than the slowdown in the economy, accounted for the sense of
crisis in August, and it was the promise of government support that later
turned the market around. It remains to be seen whether the government can
overcome the substantial political and technical obstacles to mounting an
effective rescue.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
