<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / World Economy and Business Review (13): A reversal of
strategy - Hopes will now be pinned on an improvement in competitiveness /
United Kingdom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN BRITAIN a summer of discontent on the economic front has now ended in
tears. After nearly a month of struggling to hold the pound within the ERM,
through massive intervention in the foreign exchange markets, the government
has been forced to abandon this cornerstone of its economic policy. The
devaluation option, scorned less than two weeks ago by the prime minister,
John Major, has now, in effect, had to be adopted, leaving the government to
construct a wholly new economic policy.
Yet, even with a new lower exchange rate, interest rate policy is likely to
be constrained by the need to maintain the fight against inflation. As a
result prospects for recovery from the longest peacetime recession since the
1930s look relatively unpromising. There is a big question mark over whether
Britain will, as it says it wants to, re-enter the ERM, when market
conditions look more settled, or whether it will return to a policy of
letting the pound float.
To many economists, prospects appeared completely different four months ago,
shortly after the Conservatives' surprise victory in the April 9 general
election. Economic indicators were turning up, and the end to the recession
which began around mid-1990 seemed not far away.
But this mood did not last long. Last month a survey by the Treasury showed
the median view of the economics profession was for the economy to contract
this year by 0.6 per cent, followed by a 1.6 per cent growth in 1993.
The strain on the pound of the UK's weak economic performance has in the end
proved irresistible with a small cut in German interest rates, accompanied
by a devaluation of the Italian lira in mid-September, proving insufficient
to turn away the attentions of speculators convinced that sterling was
overvalued.
The gloom had already been underlined when Professor Douglas McWilliams,
economic adviser to the Confederation of British Industry, predicted in
August that Britain faced four more quarters of contraction, with recovery
delayed until 1994. Coming from a man who has been optimistic about an
upturn - and whose views carry a lot of weight - Prof McWilliams's remarks
added to the foreboding.
Some might argue that it is when such bleak views are being expressed that
the economy is ripe for an upturn.
According to this sentiment the FT-SE 100 index of leading shares - which
between election day and the beginning of September has come off by 10 per
cent as pessimism for business prospects has set in - should soon start to
rebound. Indeed, late last week, with the first signs that the period of
uncertainty might be coming to an end, the index put in a sustained rally.
Less than propitious trends remain, however, within the UK economy:
Bank base rates, although quickly restored to 10 per cent after a temporary
rise last week to 12 per cent (and a threatened 15 per cent) in a last
desperate bid to save the ERM valuation remain extremely high for a country
struggling to climb out of recession. While the German Bundesbank maintains
its present level of interest rates - which remain high in spite of last
week's actions - Britain's potential to ease borrowing costs will remain
small.
Consumer demand, which accounts for two thirds of GDP, remains low. This is
partly because of the high overhang of consumer debt, especially mortgages,
resulting from heavy borrowing during the late 1980s' economic boom.
Consumer spending has fallen 3.5 per cent since mid-1990, while during the
last recession in 1980-81 it fell less than 2 per cent.
After a 25 per cent fall in some regions of Britain in house prices over the
past four years, the housing market remains weak, with few signs of an
upturn. According to the Bank of England, up to 1m mortgage holders, or 10
per cent of the total, have a mortgage bigger than the value of their home.
The slump in the housing market has hit particularly hard sales of
big-ticket consumer goods such as refrigerators and cookers.
While manufacturing output has shown small growth in each of the first two
quarters of this year, providing some chink of light for the economy,
prospects for the rest of 1992 do not look particularly good.
Britain's ability to inject more demand into the economy by easing fiscal
policy is diminished by its rapidly rising public sector borrowing
requirement, which looks like climbing to above Pounds 30bn this financial
year after a PSBR of Pounds 14bn in 1991-92 and a small surplus in the
previous year. Nonetheless the National Institute of Economic and Social
Research, a leading economics think tank, thinks the government might have
scope for some small measure of tax cuts or extra public spending to help a
recovery, adding up to a fiscal injection of some Pounds 2bn over the next
year.
Amid the gloom, what are the more positive elements? A fall in the value of
sterling against other European currencies, and in particular the D-Mark,
will help exports to EC partners. The prospects of companies exporting to
the US, will also have been improved .
Against this, the Treasury's previous strategy of pinning hopes for better
times on the large falls in inflation will have become much more problematic
with devaluation inevitably increasing inflationary pressures over the
medium term. To date, headline inflation, as measured by the retail prices
index, has fallen from nearly 11 per cent at the end of 1990 to below 4 per
cent in August, while the underlying year-on-year increase in average
earnings across the economy has come down over the same period from 9.75 per
cent to 6 per cent in July.
In manufacturing, largely because of the heavy falls in employment during
the past two years, productivity rises have been fairly healthy, giving some
hopes of a good platform for future industrial expansion.
Put alongside productivity increases, however, are the large falls in
factory investment during the recession. This has made some observers
pessimistic about the chances of the UK's manufacturers being able to
compete strongly over the next few years with overseas rivals, particularly
in important capital intensive areas such as electronics, cars and
production equipment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-1944</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIUDDAACFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920921
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 92 / World Economy and Business Review (15): China in the
limelight - As Japan struggles to come to terms with its success, two other
potential economic superpowers in the region are stirring / Asia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALEXANDER NICOLL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHILE Asia's most advanced economy is struggling to cope with the problems
of success, the region's other giants are stirring. Economic reform is the
fashion in most of the countries previously led by socialist-inspired
bureaucracies.
Notwithstanding Japan's problems, Asia stands out for its continued rapid
economic growth. This year, China has again burst on to the scene. If its
present growth rate is maintained its economy (though not per capita income)
would be as large as that of the US within just over 20 years.
That, as has already been seen since China embarked on the road to economic
reform, is a big if. Since the changes spearheaded by Deng Xiaoping, China's
88-year-old senior leader, began in 1979 the economy has boomed and bust
twice.
Reforms generate bursts of economic activity as regions, businesses and
individuals test out the new limits. They put tremendous pressure on the
barriers which remain in the system, especially in the price system, and
tend to push up inflation.
This year has seen another such burst. In January, Mr Deng visited the
southern coastal areas which are the showcase of Chinese reform, and urged
the whole country to speed up its efforts to boost economic growth and
change.
His visit had a strongly political aspect. Mr Deng no longer has any
official posts, but he was still engaged in a struggle for supremacy with
more conservative hardliners who fear that over-rapid reform will loosen the
Communist party's grip on power. Mr Deng believes growing prosperity is the
party's best hope of keeping power - and the crushing of the 1989
demonstrations in Tienanmen Square showed that he, like the other leaders,
was determined its position should remain unchallenged.
It took two months for the media to report Mr Deng's visit to the most open
and free area of China, only just over the border from Hong Kong. But when
they did, his message was taken up with astonishing vigour throughout the
country.
The Tienanmen Square massacre had occurred just after the beginning of an
economic austerity drive which responded to a reform-induced surge in
inflation. This year, the tight reins on the economy could be relaxed.
Credit became more free. Mr Deng's exhortations triggered a wave of
competition between regions for greater freedom along the lines of the
south's special economic zones.
Industrial production and investment soared, as all types of enterprises
sought to grow and as foreign investment, especially from overseas Chinese
in Hong Kong and Taiwan, poured in to the south.
The official target for 1992 economic growth had been 6 per cent. But
conservatives such as premier Li Peng have been forced to abandon it as the
growth rate surged to 12 per cent in the first half of the year, compared
with 7 per cent in the whole of 1991 and an average of 9 per cent since
reforms began.
Already, the planners in Beijing are worried about the economy overheating,
even though official measures of inflation so far show little cause for
alarm.
An official newspaper, the Economic Information Daily, asked in early
September: 'How long can our current fast speed of economic growth continue?
When will the 'express train' turn into a 'slow train'? Will it be like
1989, when we had to use the emergency brakes?'. It pointed out: 'Our
country has had 22 straight months of high economic growth. The pace of
growth has prompted discussion both at home and abroad on whether the
economy is overheated.'
However, the government freed the prices of a number of key materials for
manufacturing production from the beginning of September. Apart from a
tightening of banks' reserve requirements, there is little sign yet of
action to slow growth.
The challenge which the government faces is central to the transformation
away from a centrally planned economy to one in which the private sector is
given much greater play: how to maintain macroeconomic control while at the
same time loosening the restrictions on economic activity. The need is for
sharper, more delicate tools, but less bureaucracy.
China has already come a long way. Private sector activity accounts for more
than half the economy. Though state-owned industry remains a huge burden on
the budget, privately driven growth is progressively making it a smaller
problem in relative terms.
The region's other giant, India, has also undertaken a radical reform
programme which has its friends excited that the country's massive economic
potential could be released. Many of its problems were the same as China's:
unprofitable state industries and banks and excessively bureaucratic central
planning.
Unlike the government in Beijing, however, that of prime minister PV
Narasimha Rao has to change the direction of the economy in a domestic
political cauldron, with many politicians and senior bureaucrats deeply
suspicious of a policy which promotes the private sector.
Mr Manmohan Singh, the finance minister, has already abolished licensing -
the need for bureaucratic approval for corporate investments - and started
to dismantle the trade barriers and investment and currency restrictions
which had isolated the economy. But he faces political challenges in
reducing subsidies, cutting tariffs and privatising state-owned industries.
A similar reform programme is under way in Pakistan, with licensing also
abolished, all barriers to foreign investment discarded, and a rapid
programme of privatisation under way.
With communist Vietnam heading for a market economy, and Mongolia struggling
to do so in the face of huge economic difficulties, there are few countries
left in Asia whose economic policies espouse socialism (China's current
catchphrase is 'socialist market economy'). China has been exerting pressure
on North Korea, which still has a communist dictatorship, to go the same
way.
None of this yet threatens the other rapidly growing countries of south-east
and north-east Asia directly. Hong Kong and Taiwan are full participants,
through investment, in China's economic surge. But a continuation of
convincing reforms in the former socialist economies may soon have a wider
range of foreign manufacturers re-considering the location of new
export-oriented factories.
 ------------------------------------------------
                    GDP GROWTH
 ------------------------------------------------
             1987    1988    1989   1990   1991
 ------------------------------------------------
India         4.2    10.5     6.0    5.6    2.0
Pakistan      6.5     7.6     5.0    5.3    6.5
China        11.5    11.5     4.0    5.2    7.0
Vietnam               6.1     7.1    4.5    3.8
Mongolia      4.5     5.1     4.2   -2.1  -18.0
