<PROFILE>_AN-CITABADKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920919
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  19 SEP 92 / Sterling and the UK Economy: Return to ERM not imminent, PM
says
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR last night gave notice that there would be no 'imminent'
return of Britain into the European exchange rate mechanism.
Breaking his two-day silence on the UK's abandonment of the ERM in a series
of broadcast interviews, the prime minister said that the system had
revealed 'fault lines' over the past few days that provoked extraordinary
movements of currencies.
'What we have decided to do is to stand aside from the mechanism for the
time being,' he said.
Mr Major added that when Britain joined the ERM it was not a particular
fetish of the Conservative government  - it was the view of the
Confederation of British Industry, the Trades Union Congress, the Labour
party, the Liberal Democrats and most economic opinion.
In two years, membership of the ERM had meant a drop in inflation from near
11 per cent to '3.7 per cent and falling'.
He added: 'What we have seen in the last few days in the exceptional
circumstances of the market, there are fault lines in the existing working
of the ERM. We must correct those fault lines.'
Asked when Britain would return to the ERM, he replied: 'We have to address
those fault lines in the ERM before we can return. Clearly, it is not
imminent.'
He emphasised that it was 'not necessarily the case' that Britain would
re-enter at a lower rate.
On the Maastricht bill, Mr Major said it would not come back to the Commons
until the Danes had made clear what they would do. 'There is a great deal in
the Maastricht Treaty very much in the interests of British policy,' he
said.
'The treaty provides for the development of European policies outside the
Treaty of Rome, outside the European court and outside the authority of the
European Commission. We have sought that British policy for years.'
Questioned again about resignations, Mr Major said: 'There are circumstances
when ministers should resign. I do not think these circumstances apply when
an external, unforeseen event overthrows a policy which in principle is
right.
'The principle Norman Lamont was following to bring down inflation and build
prosperity was right. That was overwhelmed by circumstances that neither he
nor anybody else foresaw or could have dealt with. It was quite right for
him to stay in position. I believe he is doing a good job. I wish him to
continue to do so.'
Asked if he would therefore 'sink or swim' with the chancellor, Mr Major
replied: 'The chancellor's policy is my policy, and it is the cabinet's
policy.'
He added: 'I do not think it is the chancellor's fault. I think it is quite
unreasonable to blame the chancellor for a market movement of the sort we
have not seen for over a quarter of a century.' He said the sensible thing
for the chancellor to do was to 'stand aside from the mayhem for a time',
adding: 'And that is precisely what the chancellor did.'
The prime minister said the policy objective was to continue to bring down
inflation. 'The ERM is one means of achieving that policy. When it works
properly, it is the best policy to achieve that objective.'
</TEXT>
