FT  19 SEP 92 / Paisley boycotts talks in Dublin
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE REV Ian Paisley and his Democratic Unionist party said last night they
would not travel to Dublin on Monday for talks with the Irish government.
Mr Paisley returned to the talks on Northern Ireland's political future in
Belfast yesterday after a week-long boycott. He made clear, however, that he
would not follow the pre-agreed process and cross the border next week.
Yesterday's discussions were about the Irish government's territorial claim
over Northern Ireland. Mr Paisley withdrew from the talks last week because
he felt the constitutional claim was not high enough on the agenda.
The Ulster Unionist party will attend the Dublin meeting but it is unclear
if Mr James Molyneaux, the party leader, will be in the delegation.
The party's decision to go to Dublin has caused a rift between the two
unionist parties. The Rev William McCrea, the Democratic Unionist MP for
Mid-Ulster, yesterday insisted that all unionists should withdraw from
Monday's meeting.
